1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3 {A very interesting
move order that hasn't been especially popular until Russian Champion
Grandmaster Alexander Riazantsev has started to employ it actively. White's
two bishop's moves a bit resemble Averbach variation (Be2 and Bg5), but one of
the key ideas of this variation the possibility of kingside assault by means
of advancing g and h-pawns.} c5 {Almost in every line of King's Indian Black
has the choice of either to play the more common e7-e5 or try to get Benoni
type of play with c7-c5-move. This line is not an exception.} 7. d5 {I believe
this is White's best bet. Riazantsev has tried} (7. dxc5 {in two games.} Qa5 8.
f3 {White also tried} (8. Bd2 {A very recent game here saw} dxc5 $5 9. e5 Ne8
10. f4 f6 11. Nd5 Qd8 12. Be3 {1/2-1/2 (33) Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2671)-Jones,
G (2671) Dubai 2017 and now Black could have played} e6 $1 13. Nc3 Qe7 14. Nf3
Nc6 {with good game for Black.}) 8... dxc5 9. e5 Rd8 $1 {this is stronger than}
(9... Nfd7 10. f4 Nc6 11. Nf3 Rd8 {Riazantsev,A (2671)-Martinovic,S (2550)
Tallinn 2016 Now} 12. Bd2 $1 Qc7 13. O-O Nb6 14. Qe1 $14 {would secure White's
pleasant edge, due to his space advantage.}) 10. Qa4 Qxa4 11. Nxa4 Nfd7 {
Worth considering} (11... Ne8 $5 12. Bxc5 Nc6 13. f4 f6 $44 {with interesting
compensation.}) 12. f4 Nc6 13. O-O-O $146 {This looks like a decent try to
improve on the game} (13. Nf3 b6 14. O-O Bb7 {and Black was just fine in
Riazantsev,A (2671)-Saric,I (2652) Tallinn 2016}) 13... b6 14. Bf3 Bb7 15. Nh3
{and White might have some pull, thanks to his space superiority.}) 7... e6 {
By playing e7-e6, Black forces the transition into a Benoni type of structure.}
({Another essential idea to check is} 7... b5 8. cxb5 a6 {playing in the
spirit of Benko Gambit.} 9. a4 $1 {This is a typical idea in such positions.
In Benko type of positions, Black sacrifices a pawn to open the b-file for his
major pieces. The pressure along the b-file is very well supported by the
g7-bishop. With his last move, White is trying to establish a firm control
over the b5-square. In this way, he prevents Black from putting pressure along
the b-file.} Qa5 10. Bd2 $1 {Another precise prophylactic move. As we are
going to see on many occasions, the opposition along the a5-e1 diagonal is
very annoying for Black.} axb5 ({The line} 10... Qb4 11. f3 Nfd7 {has been
tried in a couple of games. So far, Black was in a pretty good shape in this
line. At this point, however, a very strong novelty would be} 12. a5 $1 $146 {
[%csl Rb4] making use of the position of Black's queen.} axb5 (12... Qxb2 13.
Ra2 Qb4 14. Qc2 {[%cal Ga2a4] Black is in trouble since the queen is in danger.
}) 13. Na4 $1 {The point behind White's previous move} Qd4 14. Bxb5 $16 {
and White is just clearly better.}) 11. Bxb5 Ba6 12. Ra3 $1 {This is a very
important move in this structure. It is important to make sure that the rook
is protected in a case of massive exchanges on b5.} Nbd7 13. Nf3 Bxb5 14. Nxb5
Qa6 (14... Qb6 15. Qc2 {This move would have been quite risky with a rook on
a1 since there is a queen sacrifice on b5.}) 15. Qc2 Rac8 16. O-O {White was
clearly better in Johansen-Nisipeanu, Sydney 2014. Black has no compensation
for the missing pawn.}) 8. Nf3 exd5 9. cxd5 {We have reached a typical Benoni
position. At this point, I would like to clarify the ideas of both sides.
White has two main plans in this position: 1) Put pressure on the weak d6 -
pawn by means of Bf4 and Nf3-d2-c4 2) Go for a central strategy by playing
Nf3-d2-c4 followed by f2-f4 and e4-e5 Sometimes, it is possible to combine
these ideas, For example, when the bishop is on f4, it is possible to play Bg3
followed by f2-f4 and e4-e5. As a rule, in this structure, Black is playing on
the queenside. The most important positional idea for him is to gain space on
the queenside through a7-a6 followed by b7-b5. The queenside pawn expansion is
perfectly supported by the g7-bishop. Also, Black always tries to make use of
the semi-open e-file in order to put pressure on the e4-pawn. When dealing
with pawn structures, it is always important to discuss possible piece
exchanges. Given the fact that White enjoys a considerable space advantage,
exchanges of minor pieces are favorable for Black. Black's worst piece in this
structure is the c8-bishop. Usually, he is trying to exchange this bishop for
the f3-knight. Knight exchanges are also favorable for Black, but he should
not exchange the dark-squared bishops. The exchange of the dark-squared
bishops reduces Black's active possibilities on the queenside and weakens the
kingside. In general, in Benoni type of positions, we must be prepared for a
complex positional battle.} ({Harmless is} 9. exd5 Bf5 10. O-O Ne4 11. Nxe4
Bxe4 12. Bd3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nd7 {and Black comfortably equalized in
Serper-Filippov, V Novgorod 1995}) 9... b5 {Very important and critical move.
In many Benoni type of positions, this is a way for Black to solve his opening
problems. It goes without saying that Black has other moves as well:} ({After} 
9... Re8 {White should react with the typical} 10. Nd2 {The knight not only
protects the e4-pawn but at some moment can occupy the ideal c4-square.} Na6 {
[%cal Ga6c7,Ga8b8,Gb7b5] Besides a7-a6, this is another typical way to prepare
the b7-b5 advance. Black intends to follow with Na6-c7, Rb8, and b7-b5. The
main drawback of this plan is the passive c7-knight.} 11. O-O Nc7 {[%cal Gb7b5]
Now, 12...b7-b5 is already a threat because of the vulnerable e4-pawn. That is
why White should play} 12. a4 b6 {This is a move with multiple ideas. After
b7-b6, Black is ready to answer the move Nc4 with Ba6 in any moment. Later on,
he wants to follow with a7-a6 and b6-b5 after exchanging his bishop for the
c4-knight. Another idea is to prepare b6-b5 gradually. For example, ...Rb8
followed by a7-a6 and b6-b5 is an option. With a pawn on b7, White could
answer a7-a6 with a4-a5.} 13. Bg5 {The pin along the h4-d8 diagonal always
disrupts the coordination in Black's camp. With a knight being pinned, Black
can not make use of the potential of his g7-bishop.} Rb8 {This position
occurred in two games. Black intends to follow with a7-a6 and b6-b5. At this
point, a very nice idea for improving White's play might be} 14. Bb5 $5 Nxb5 ({
After} 14... Bd7 {White makes use of the pin along the h4-d8 diagonal by
playing} 15. Qf3 $1 {Black's pieces are tied.}) 15. axb5 Qc7 16. h3 {Since
White neutralized Black's queenside counterplay, Black is doomed to passivity.
Now, White's plan is obvious. He wants to prepare his central strategy by
means of Nc4 followed by Re1, f2-f4 and e4-e5.}) ({Quite a typical idea in
Benoni type of positions is} 9... Bg4 {Black wants to give his passive bishop
for White's strong knight. When possible, White is advised to avoid such an
exchange.} 10. Nd2 {Of course! The knight is heading for c4.} Bxe2 11. Qxe2
Nbd7 12. O-O a6 13. a4 {As a rule, the move a7-a6 is always well met by a2-a4!
We should prevent our opponent from gaining space on the queenside by means of
b7-b5.} Rc8 {This move was played in the game Riazantsev, A (2646)-Yuffa, D 
(2503) Chelyabinsk 2016. Black's idea is to execute the advance c5-c5 in a
suitable moment.} ({The game Eingorn, V (2528)-Hainke, G (2308) Bad Wiessee
2016 went} 13... Qe7 {Black connects his rooks and prepares the maneuver
Nf6-e8-c7 followed by b7-b5. To prevent this idea, I believe White should have
played} 14. Bg5 $1 {We already know how annoying this pin could be.} h6 {
Black is trying to get rid of the pin as soon as possible. If he opts for a
passive strategy, White could play Nc4 followed by Rae1, f2-f4 and e4-e5.} 15.
Bh4 g5 16. Bg3 {The d6-pawn and f5-square are very weak. Also, Black can not
create an activity on the queenside. White's advantage is out of question.})
14. a5 $1 {This typical move allows White to fix Black's queenside pawns. Now,
Black can not answer the move Nc4 with Nb6. The play might continue} Re8 15. f4
b5 16. axb6 Nxb6 17. Kh1 $1 {This is a very important prophylactic move. When
f2-f4 is played, we should keep an eye on the a7-g1 diagonal. For example,
with a king on g1, Black can play ...Nfxd5 followed by ...Rxe3 and ...Bd4,
pinning the queen. Now, White will combine his central strategy with pressure
against the weak a6-pawn.}) 10. e5 $1 {When your opponent goes for a flank
attack, you should strike in the center!} ({Black's idea becomes clear after} 
10. Bxb5 Nxe4 $1 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ $13 {with a complex position.}) 10... dxe5 {
Another Black move here} ({After} 10... Ng4 11. Bg5 Qb6 12. exd6 b4 13. Ne4 f5
$6 14. Ned2 {White was much better in Lampert, J (2500)-Mueer, S (2237) Erfurt
2016. The strong passed pawn on d5 as well as the important outpost on c4 make
White's position very promising.}) 11. Bxc5 (11. Bxb5 {also deserves attention.
}) 11... Re8 12. Bxb5 e4 13. Nd4 {Interesting to check the following idea} (13.
Bxe8 $5 exf3 14. Bxf7+ Kxf7 15. Qxf3 Bg4 16. Qf4 Nbd7 17. Be3 $14) 13... Nfd7
14. Ba3 Qb6 {this position occurred in Gulko-Becerra Rivero, Saint Louis 2009.
I believe White should have played} 15. Nde2 $1 $146 {With the obvious idea to
complete the development. After} Ba6 16. Qa4 e3 17. O-O {Black has to prove
his compensation.} *

