1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3 {In this chapter, I
will examine some of the most popular sidelines .} Nc6 (6... a6 {Quite a
tricky waiting move. Later Black either goes for c6 with the idea of b7-b5 or
can try to enter a Benoni type of position by playing c7-c5. That is why White
should play in a very flexible way.} 7. h3 $1 {I like this prophylactic move,
which covers g4-square.} ({After the more natural} 7. Nf3 {Black can play} Bg4
8. O-O Nfd7 {To my great surprise, I discovered that Black has a pretty decent
counterplay here. He can either play c7-c5 or attack the center by means of
Nc6 followed by e7-e5.}) 7... Nbd7 {Another line here} ({In a case of} 7... c6
{I suggest} 8. e5 $5 {This seems to me more interesting than} (8. a4) 8... Nfd7
{After this move, Black's position is too passive.} ({Another option is} 8...
Ne8 {keeping the option to take with a piece in a case of 9.exd6.} 9. f4 {
This is one of the points of delaying the move Nf3. Now White can maintain his
space advantage. After} b5 10. Nf3 {White got a nice edge in Williams, S (2461)
-Dignam,M (2194) Douglas 2005}) 9. exd6 exd6 10. Nf3 b5 11. O-O bxc4 12. Bxc4
Nb6 {This position occurred in Heimann, A (2560)-Hug, W (2473) Switzerland
2016. Now, White could have played} 13. Bg5 $1 {It turns out that Black's
queen doesn't have a good square in this position.} Qc7 {This is relatively
the best continuation. Nevertheless, White will be able to create an annoying
opposition along the c-file by playing Rc1.} ({The idea to exchange the
dark-squared bishops doesn't seem to be promising either. After} 13... Bf6 14.
Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Ne4 Qd8 16. Bb3 $16 {White is clearly better in this position.
He has better development and pawn structure. Furthermore, after the exchange
of the dark-squared bishops, Black's kingside is considerably weakened.}) 14.
Bb3 N8d7 15. Rc1 {White has a pleasant advantage.}) 8. Nf3 c5 9. O-O {This is
the best move from a positional point of view. When you have a space advantage,
you should keep the tension in the position. In this way, the pieces of your
opponent will be limited in their actions.} ({After} 9. d5 b5 $1 {Black gets a
lot of counterplay.}) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 {Due to Nbd7 move Black's set-up is
far from optimal against White's Maroczy Bind. With a knight on c6 (instead of
d7), Black could have exchanged a pair of knights by means of ...Nxd4. Now, it
is impossible to create counterplay.} Nc5 (10... b6 {would run into} 11. Nc6 $1
Qe8 12. Nd5 {with an excellent initiative for White.}) 11. Qc2 Bd7 12. Rfd1 Rc8
13. Rac1 Qe8 14. b4 Na4 15. Nd5 $1 {and White maintained a solid advantage in
Siebrecht, S (2457)-Tabatt, H (2347) Bad Liebenzell 2010. Black is doomed to
passivity.}) ({After} 6... c6 {, quite interesting is} 7. g4 $5 ({White can
definitely transpose to Gligoric variation by means of} 7. Nf3 {but I think
the aggressive 7. g4 should work well}) 7... Qa5 {other options are:} (7... e5
8. d5 {[%emt 0:00:03] would transpose to Chapter}) ({The attempt to strike in
the center by playing} 7... d5 {seems interesting. Here I found the following
promising line for White} 8. cxd5 $146 (8. e5 Ne4 {was very unclear}) 8... cxd5
9. e5 Ne4 10. h4 $1 {and White might have interesting play on the kingside,
for example:} Qa5 11. h5 Nc6 12. Kf1 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Qxc3 14. Nh3 {White's
initiative on the kingside seems to be very dangerous.}) ({Too slow is} 7... a6
{[%cal Gb7b5] preparing the typical b7-b5.} 8. g5 Nfd7 {This position occurred
in Anikonov, D (2109)-Loskutov, O (2396) Novokuznetsk 2013 White should have
continued his kingside play through} 9. h4 $146 b5 10. h5 $40 {with a
dangerous initiative.}) 8. f3 e5 9. d5 cxd5 {This move clarifies the situation
in the center.} ({Maybe more interesting for Black would be} 9... b5 10. g5 {
Accepting the challenge.} ({The positional} 10. Kf2 {is also interesting.})
10... Nh5 11. cxb5 cxb5 12. Bxb5 Ba6 {This move allows the exchange of the
queens.} ({Stronger would have been} 12... Nf4 {Nevertheless, after} 13. Bf1 f5
14. gxf6 Bxf6 15. Qa4 Bh4+ 16. Kd2 Qd8 17. Rc1 {we have a double-edged play,
but Black has to prove his compensation for being a pawn down.}) 13. Qa4 Qxa4
14. Bxa4 $16 {White was just healthy pawn up Uddenfeldt, D (2412)-Fransson, P 
(2345) Sweden 2009}) 10. cxd5 {We have reached a typical KID structure.
Despite the move g2-g4, White's plan is to play on the queenside. In many
positions, it turns out that the advance g2-g4 makes difficult for Black to
create a kingside counterplay by preparing f7-f5. There are two important
positional factors for White in this position: 1) the control over the c-file
2) the weak d6-pawn One of White's main positional ideas is to exchange the
queens. Almost every endgame will be difficult for Black because the d6-pawn
is a long-term weakness. On the other hand, Black has two main plans at his
disposal: 1) start active actions on the kingside by means of f7-f5 2) go for
a queenside play by playing b7-b5-b4 followed by Nb8-d7-c5 Since White had
already gained space on the kingside by playing g2-g4, in this position Black
can consider taking energetic actions on the queenside. This plan works well
when White is behind in the development. Nevertheless, if Black doesn't
achieve something concrete, White will be better in a long-term because the
advance b7-b5-b5 creates a lot of weaknesses. Here is a sample line} Bd7 11.
Qd2 Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gb7b5,Gb5b4] Intending to follow with Nc5, and b7-b5-b4.}
12. a3 Rfb8 {This position arose in the game Amura, C (2405)-Izquierdo, D 
(2295) Argentina 1991 Now the simple} 13. Nh3 $146 b5 14. O-O $14 {would leave
White in control over the position. Black doesn't have concrete achievements
while White is ready to start playing on the queenside.}) 7. d5 {The most
principled reaction.} Ne5 8. f4 {Now Black has obviously two options} Neg4 {
This is the most principled move. Black is trying to make use of his superior
development.} ({After} 8... Ned7 {White has} 9. Nh3 $1 {Well-known idea which
is quite typical for Samisch Variation of KID. Whenever Black develops his
knight to d7 closing the way of the light-squared bishop, White gets the
option of developing his knight to h3. The knight is heading for the perfect
f2-square. From this position, he protects the e4-pawn and takes under control
the important g4-square.} e6 {Black wants to open up the position before White
manages to complete the development.} ({Another way to attack the center would
be} 9... c6 {.After} 10. Nf2 cxd5 11. cxd5 Nb6 {Besides the normal and
positionally sound 12.0-0, White can even consider playing} 12. g4 $5 {The
idea is to answer} e6 13. dxe6 Bxe6 {with the powerful} 14. f5 $16 {White had
developed a very strong initiative in the game Schreiner,P (2472)-Reich,T 
(2362) Aschach 2016}) 10. dxe6 fxe6 11. Bf3 {White's space advantage promises
him a nice edge here. The following game went} Qe7 12. O-O a5 13. Qd2 Nc5 $2
14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. e5 Nd7 16. b3 {with a strategically winning position in So,
W (2760)-Zapata,A (2464) Las Vegas 2015}) 9. Bd2 {It turns out that Black has
problems to find decent squares for his knights. In the game Sokolov - Van
Foreest, 2016, Black played} Nh6 ({Dubious is} 9... h5 $6 {. After} 10. h3 Nh6
11. Nf3 e6 12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Qc1 $1 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gf4f5] The awkward
position of Black's knight on h6 starts to tell. Now, White threatens to play
14. f4-f5. Vallifuoco,G (2350)-Martorelli,A (2235) Chianciano 1988}) 10. Nf3 c6
11. O-O $5 cxd5 12. cxd5 b5 {With this move, Black wants to create an activity
before White manages to consolidate his position. It turns out, however, that
White is just in time to establish a coordination in his camp.} ({It's quite
dangerous for Black to go after b2-pawn. For example, after} 12... Qb6+ 13. Kh1
Qxb2 14. e5 $1 $36 {, White develops a tremendous initiative for the pawn.})
13. Bd3 b4 14. Na4 Bd7 15. Kh1 Nh5 16. Rc1 Qa5 17. b3 $14 {and White was
better in Sokolov, I (2623)-Van Foreest, J (2615) Hoogeveen 2016. He completed
the development and protected his strong pawn center. Black has structural
weaknesses and passive knights.} *

