1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3 e5 7. d5 {A very
important position for this variation. Black has four main possibilities:} Na6
{Quite a typical move for King's Indian Defence. Since White had already
played d4-d5, Black's knight is heading for the important c5-square.} ({
The main alternative is} 7... a5 {This is a typical move for the current
structure. Before starting active actions on the kingside, Black wants to
restrict White's queenside play. At the same time, the move 7...a5 secures the
c5-square for the knight.} 8. g4 {This move is one of the main points of
White's set-up. It is important to point out that White's idea is not to
create a mating attack on the kingside - 8.g4 is a prophylactic move! Later on,
White intends to continue gaining space on the kingside by means of h2-h4-h5.
In this way, he will prevent Black from taking active actions on the kingside.
After restricting Black's kingside play, White can start gradually preparing
his queenside strategy.} Na6 9. h4 (9. g5 {is an interesting alternative.
However, it seems to me very unclear due to the following game} Nd7 10. h4 Ndc5
11. Qd2 c6 12. f3 a4 {Black has a decent counterplay in this position. Ѕ-Ѕ 
(21) Riazantsev,A (2671)-Amonatov,F (2592) St Petersburg 2015}) 9... Nc5 10. f3
{transposing to Na6 line.}) ({Sometimes, Black goes for} 7... c6 {Usually a
bit slow, but the move to take into consideration.} 8. g4 {This is more in the
spirit of our line.} ({It goes without saying, that White has} 8. Nf3 {at his
disposal transposing to Gligoric variation.}) {The logical development of play
here would be} 8... cxd5 9. cxd5 Qa5 {Black starts active actions on the
queenside. He is planning to make use of the c-file to overtake the initiative.
He usually develops his pieces in the following way: Na6-c5 followed by Rfc8.
Nevertheless, we know that Black's queenside initiative is temporary. From a
structural point of view, White has the upper hand on the queenside (the
d5-pawn gives him a space advantage). If White manages to neutralize the
temporary activity of Black's pieces, in the long run, he will be better.
Every endgame would be difficult for Black due to White's space advantage and
the weak d6-pawn.} 10. f3 Na6 11. Qd2 ({Another possibility is} 11. Nh3 $5 Bd7
12. Nf2 Rfc8 13. a3 {I prefer White's position here. Later on, White will
transfer his king to g2 and double the rooks along the c-file. We know that
massive exchanges which lead to an endgame usually favor White. At the same
time, it is not clear how Black can create immediate threats.}) 11... Bd7 12.
Nh3 Rfc8 13. Nf2 Nc5 {Deshmukh,A (2228)-Pradeep,K (2316) Sonipat 2017 now, the
natural} 14. Rb1 $1 {would leave White with some edge. It's very important that
} Na4 {is strongly met by} 15. Nb5 {with advantage.}) ({The line} 7... Nbd7 8.
g4 Nc5 9. f3 {just transposes to Na6.}) 8. g4 {White opts for his usual
strategy in this line - restrict Black's counterplay by taking space on the
kingside and start active actions on the queenside.} Nc5 9. f3 a5 {Black plays
in a classical fashion. With his last move, he prevents White from playing
b2-b5. Furthermore, Black is even ready to go for an active play by means of
c7-c6 followed by a5-a4, and Qa5.} ({Nevertheless, Black's most principled
choice seems to be} 9... h5 10. g5 Nh7 11. h4 {[%emt 0:00:04] which will be
covered in Chapter}) 10. h4 {Now, Black faces a choice again. He can either
start playing on the queenside by means of 10...Bd7 followed by c7-c6, or look
for a kingside counterplay by playing 10...h5.} Bd7 ({After} 10... h5 11. g5 {
Black should probably play} Nh7 {This is the best square for the knight in
this structure. Black idea is to put pressure on the g5-pawn by means of f7-f6.
The g5-pawn is White's main asset in this position. This pawn gives him space
and restricts Black's minor pieces. With a pawn on g5, Black can not create
counterplay on the kingside. If White manages to protect this pawn and to
start playing on the queenside, his position would be strategically winning.} (
{Other retreats of the knight seem to be too passive. For example, after} 11...
Ne8 12. Qd2 {Black can not put effective pressure on g5. That is why he is
forced to start playing on the queenside where White has the upper hand.} Bd7
13. O-O-O a4 14. Nh3 Qb8 15. Nf2 c6 {This position was reached in the game
Sadler, M (2440)-Le Quang, K (2240) Cappelle-la-Grande 1991. Now} 16. Kb1 {
would leave White firmly in control. Black runs out of useful moves. The
dark-squared bishop and the f8-rook are out of play. Furthermore, due to the
weakness of the d6-pawn, Black can not improve the position of his e8-knight.})
({Maybe slightly more precise is} 11... Nfd7 {Nevertheless, the spirit of the
position doesn't change.} 12. Nh3 Nb6 {Five games have reached this position,
but White has never played the natural} 13. Nf2 $146 {The play may continue} c6
14. Qd2 cxd5 {through a different move order this position occurred in
Debashis, D (2472)-Firouzja, A (2456) Doha 2016. Now, instead of 15. exd5,
White could have opted for either} 15. cxd5 ({or} 15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. exd5 e4 17.
Nfxe4 Bf5 18. Ng3 Qd7 19. Kf2) 15... Bd7 16. Nb5 {with an advantage in both
cases.}) 12. Qd2 f6 13. O-O-O fxg5 14. hxg5 {We have reached a typical
position for this line. It turns out that White manages to hold the g5-pawn.
Later on, he can gradually start playing on the queenside.} Bd7 {Black is
planning to play 15...Qe7 and to double the rooks on the f-file.} ({Another
approach would be} 14... a4 15. Nh3 Bxh3 16. Rxh3 Rf4 {Quite a typical
exchange sacrifice for this structure. By sacrificing an exchange, Black
intends to open the long diagonal for his bishop. At the same time, now, White
must find a way to deal with the pressure on g5.} 17. Rg1 ({Obviously, White
should refrain from winning the exchange} 17. Bxf4 exf4 $44 {Black
dark-squared bishop becomes too powerful Ree, H (2460)-Timman, J (2590)
Nijmegen 1977}) 17... Qe7 18. Kb1 Raf8 {This position was reached in the game
Chabanon, J (2458)-Degraeve, J (2586) Agen 2016. Now, White could have played}
19. Rhg3 $146 {defending the important g5-pawn, which restricts Black's minor
pieces and slowly preparing his play on the queenside. For example, Bd1
targeting the a4-pawn is a very good option. I think strategically White has a
very clear edge.}) 15. Nh3 Qe7 16. Kb1 Rf7 17. Nf2 Raf8 18. Rdg1 Rf4 {
Riazantsev,A (2646) -Amonatov, F (2592) St Petersburg 2015. Now, the simple}
19. Rg2 $1 {would actually defend the g5-pawn thanks to the following elegant
tactical trick} Nxg5 $2 20. Bxc5 dxc5 21. d6 $1 cxd6 22. Nd5 Qd8 23. Nxf4 Rxf4
(23... exf4 {loses to} 24. Qd5+) 24. Rhg1 {with a huge advantage.}) 11. h5 c6
12. Qd2 cxd5 13. cxd5 a4 14. Nh3 Qa5 {So far, both sides are making the most
natural moves. White gained a lot of space on the kingside while Black started
an active play on the other side of the board.} ({Another game saw} 14... Rc8
15. Nf2 Qa5 {This position was reached in the game Riazantsev, A (2671)-Seeman,
T (2420) Tallinn 2016. Now White should play} 16. Nb5 $1 Qa6 ({it goes without
saying, that endgame after} 16... Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 {is favorable for White.}) 17.
Na3 b5 18. Nc2 $14 {With classical positional advantage. The knight is heading
for the b4-square. White is dominating on both flanks.}) 15. Nf2 {White's plan
is quite simple. After transferring his king to g2, he will start fighting for
the c-file. It is important to mention that in some positions White can even
create threats on the kingside by playing Bh6.} b5 16. Kf1 b4 {In order not to
find himself in a passive position, Black immediately starts gaining space on
the queenside. The advance b7-b5-b4, however, has some serious drawbacks. If
White manages to coordinate his minor pieces, the weakness of the squares c4
and c6 will tell in the long run.} 17. Ncd1 Bb5 {all this occurred in Rivas
Pastor, M (2511)-Narciso Dublan, M (2511) Leon 2006} ({Maybe better for Black
was} 17... Rfc8 18. Kg2 Bb5 {but even here White maintains pleasant edge after}
19. Bxb5 Qxb5 20. Rc1 Nfd7 21. Bh6 $14 {When all Black's pieces are far away
from the kingside, White can go for this exchange. Now, Black should take care
of his vulnerable king.}) {White missed a very powerful idea} 18. Bxc5 $1 Bxe2+
(18... dxc5 19. Ne3 {also much better for White.}) 19. Kxe2 Qb5+ (19... Qxc5 {
obviously runs into} 20. Nd3 {winning the b4-pawn.}) 20. Ke1 dxc5 21. Rc1 {
and Black probably has to go for} c4 {in order to avoid a blockade on c4.} 22.
h6 $1 Bh8 23. Qe2 Rfc8 24. Ne3 {winning the c4-pawn with a questionable
compensation for Black.} *

