1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3 e5 7. d5 Na6 8. g4 Nc5
9. f3 h5 {In my opinion a very challenging approach - instead of playing 9...
a5, Black opts for a kingside counterplay. White should go for our familiar
structure which arises after the moves} 10. g5 Nh7 11. h4 {This is by far the
best move in the position. In Chapter 3, I have already explained the basic
plans in this structure.} ({After} 11. Qd2 f6 {, White has problems to keep
his g5-pawn. For example, after} 12. h4 ({In a case of} 12. gxf6 Bxf6 13. O-O-O
h4 $13 {Black is just fine here. Now, he intends to exchange the dark-squared
bishops by means of Bg5. That is why White should have played h4 on move 11.})
12... fxg5 13. hxg5 {The exchange sacrifice} Rf4 $1 {is very powerful. The
game might continue} 14. Bxf4 exf4 15. Qxf4 Be5 16. Qe3 Qf8 $44 {Black has a
tremendous compensation. The dark-squares in White's camp are very weak. Ѕ-Ѕ
(34) Agrest, E (2485)-Korsunsky, A St Petersburg 1992}) 11... f6 12. gxf6 {
This decision is practically forced. Since the structure has changed, I would
like to explain again the plans of both sides. The position is highly
unbalanced from a positional point of view. Now, Black's minor pieces are not
limited in their actions. Furthermore, Black intends to build a strong
pressure against the h4-pawn. On the other hand, in this structure, White has
at his disposal the semi-open g-file. Later on, after transferring his king to
the queenside, White can put pressure on the g6-pawn. At this point, we should
point out something very important. Theoretically speaking, White should play
on the queenside (the d5-pawn gives him a space advantage). On the other hand,
since White's king will be there, Black can create some queenside play by
means of c7-c6 and a7-a5-a4. In a long-term, however, especially in the
endgame, White will win the game on the queenside.} ({After} 12. Qd2 fxg5 13.
hxg5 Rf4 $1 {We transpose to the variation given above.}) 12... Bxf6 13. Bf2
Be7 {[%cal Gf8f4] Black is planning to increase the pressure on the h4-pawn.
We should protect it at any price! At this point, I suggest the creative} 14.
Kd2 $1 {White wants to defend the h4-pawn through 15.Qe1. At the same time,
the king is heading for the queenside.} Rf4 15. Qe1 Bd7 16. b3 {Trying to
prevent the possible Na4-idea.} ({Interesting would be} 16. Kc2 {with the idea
to meet} Na4 {by means of} 17. Nxa4 Bxa4+ 18. b3 Bd7 19. Rd1 {White managed to
protect the h4-pawn and to coordinate his queenside. Now, he can follow with
20.Nh3, kicking the rook backward. Later on, he can consider putting pressure
on the g6-pawn.}) 16... a5 {The position was reached in the game David, A 
(2569) -Nitin, S (2427) New Delhi 2017. Here, instead of the unclear 17.Bf1 c6
which was seen in the game, I recommend} 17. Kc2 {As usual, White wants to
complete the development of his queenside pieces before playing Nh3.} c6 18.
Rd1 Na6 {Through a different move order, this position occurred in the game
Ozturk, K (2262)-Nitin, S (2428) Graz 2017 I believe that White should have
played} 19. Nh3 $1 {not fearing of} Rxh4 20. Bxh4 (20. dxc6 bxc6 21. Bxh4 Bxh4
22. Qd2 Nf8 23. Rdg1 {also an option for White.}) 20... Bxh4 21. Qg1 Qf6 22.
Nf2 $14 {and it's hard to believe Black has fully sufficient compensation.} *

