1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3 Nbd7 {This is a
classical way to prepare the e7-e5 advance. It is very important for White to
know how to react here because some KID players play Nbd7 against pretty much
everything. Here, I believe that the creative} 7. g4 $5 {fits very well in
White's overall concept in this system.} ({Of course, White can transpose to
Gligoric System by playing} 7. Nf3) 7... c5 {This is the only independent
possibility for Black. Black wants to obtain Benoni, or Benko type of
structure.} ({The usual} 7... e5 8. d5 Nc5 9. f3 {just transposes to the 6...
e5 variation.}) 8. g5 {I believe it's important to insert this move, since
after} (8. d5 {Black has the strong} b5 $1 9. g5 Ne8 10. cxb5 a6 {and I am not
a big fan of White's position. Advancing g-pawn is usually not very helpful in
Benko type of positions. Perdomo,L (2430)-Goncalves,R (1979) Florianopolis 2016
}) 8... Ne8 {Up to this moment, Black has always responded with 8...Ne8.} ({
An interesting improvement could be} 8... Nh5 $146 {In my opinion White has to
accept challenge} 9. Bxh5 gxh5 10. Nge2 {with very complicated game, which
requires further investigation. Nevertheless, White's position seems
preferable to me due to Black's weakened kingside structure.}) 9. Nf3 {There
is only one game in this position so far. After} cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nc5 11. h4 Nc7
12. Qd2 N7e6 13. O-O-O {White's position is very promising. Later on, he can
proceed with his kingside attack by preparing the h4-h5 advance. Eidelmann, V 
(2036)-Kollberg, L (2157) Bad Sooden 2004} *

