1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Be3 Na6 {This is one of
the most flexible ways to meet White's set-up. Black develops a piece and
keeps all the options open. Later on, depending on White's plan, he can attack
the center either with c7-c5, or e7-e5.} 7. Nf3 {In my opinion, this is the
most appropriate moment to enter the so-called Gligoric Variation of King's
Indian Defence. When using this move order to transpose to Gligoric Variation,
we reduce the number of Black's options in this line.} ({If White opts for the
typical} 7. g4 {, Black is not obliged to play 7...e5 any longer. Instead, he
can go for} c5 8. d5 (8. g5 $6 {runs into the following nice sequence} Ng4 $1
9. Bxg4 Bxg4 10. Qxg4 cxd4 11. Bxd4 Bxd4 {and Black was already better in
Hawkins, J (2583)-Warmerdam, M (2350) chess.com INT 2017}) 8... e6 9. g5 Nh5 $1
{and I have the feeling that White's play was too aggressive. He started
pushing his kingside pawns, while the situation in the center remains unclear.}
) 7... e5 8. O-O {Obviously in this position Black has a wide choice. He has
the following moves - 8...Ng4, 8...c6, 8...Qe8, 8...h6, 8...Qe7, and 8...exd4.
In the current Chapter, I cover the popular 8...c6. The moves 8...h6, 8...Qe7
and 8...exd4 are dealt with in Chapter 7. Chapter 8 features the move 8...Qe8.
Chapter 9 and 10 deal with the main move 8...Ng4. Before start dealing with
all the theoretical subtleties of this line, I would like to explain the
"philosophy" of the position. It is obvious that White has space advantage and
comfortably developed pieces. As a rule, when you have a space advantage, you
should keep the tension. In this way, you keep your opponent's pieces busy
with the defense of the most important points. In this structure, White
usually tries to provoke Black to play exd4. In this case, thanks to the c4
and e4-pawns, White enjoys a lasting space advantage. Black has great
difficulties to create counterplay. On the other hand, Black tries to provoke
White to clarify the situation in the center by playing d4-d5 or dxe5. If
White goes for d4-d5, we have a typical KID structure in which the plans of
both sides are clear - White plays on the queenside while Black is trying to
create counterplay on the kingside. Furthermore, the advance d4-d5 allows
Black to bring his a6-knight into play through Nc5. The structure arising
after dxe5 is also playable for Black. His main idea is to make use of the
weak d4-square (usually he does it by transferring one of the knights to the
e6-square). Of course, White can gain space on the queenside by playing a2-a3
followed by b2-b4 and c4-c5. In such a case, the position remains balanced.} c6
{We have reached a position which is very important for the theory of the
variation. With his last move, Black takes the control over the important
d5-square and makes room for a possible sortie of his queen. In some positions,
he can put pressure on White's center by means of ...Ng4 followed by Qb6. At
this point I suggest} 9. Re1 $5 {A very interesting idea, which avoids the
main line 9. d5. White is waiting for Black to clarify his plan while playing
useful move. Since Black had already played c7-c6, the move 9.d5 would be more
justified - the d6-pawn is already weak. As I have already pointed out,
however, White should avoid clarifying the position in the center.} Re8 {
Once again, by putting an indirect pressure on the e4-pawn, Black wants to
provoke White to clarify the situation in the center by playing 10.d5 or 10.
dxe5. This will be our main move, but certainly Black has other options:} ({
First of all, White is well-prepared for} 9... exd4 $6 10. Nxd4 Re8 11. f3 d5 {
Without this break, Black is doomed to defend a passive position. The ideas in
this structure were very well explained by GM Petar Arnaudov in his articles
for Issues 11 and 12 of Modern Chess Magazine.} ({Another typical aggressive
plan for Black is} 11... Nh5 {Black wants to make us of the weakened dark
squares by playing Qh4 and Be5. White, however, is very well prepared for this
idea.} 12. Qd2 Qh4 13. Bf1 Be5 14. g3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Bxg3 {This position was
reached in the game Khismatullin, D (2647)-Kokarev, D (2623) Khanty-Mansiysk
2012. Here, the price} 16. Bg5 $1 Bxe1 17. Rxe1 Qg3+ 18. Bg2 $18 {would have
decided the game.}) 12. cxd5 Nxd5 ({Even worse is} 12... cxd5 13. Bb5 $1 {
The idea to spoil Black's coordination by attacking the e8-rook is typical for
this structure. One of the games in this line continued} Rf8 $2 14. e5 Ne8 15.
Bxa6 bxa6 16. Nc6 Qc7 17. Nxd5 $18 {with a winning advantage in Malek,D (2398)
-Alexiadis,H (2296) Pardubice 2015}) 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bxa6 bxa6 15. Nc6 Qf6 {
Black is trying to play as actively as possible. Otherwise, White will be just
a pawn up.} 16. exd5 Qxb2 17. Rb1 Qxa2 18. d6 Bd7 19. Ne7+ Kh8 20. Bd4 $18 {
and White got a decisive advantage in Nyback-Bekker Jensen, Bremen 2013}) ({
The most popular move is} 9... Ng4 {By attacking the e3-bishop, Black wants to
weaken the d4-pawn. If White doesn't play very precisely, his opponent will
create a tremendous piece activity.} 10. Bg5 f6 {Black should go for this move
since there is no suitable square for Black's queen. Let's take a look at the
alternatives.} ({Several games featured} 10... Qc7 {Stranegly enough, nobody
played} 11. Qd2 $146 {which seems to me very logical. White's pieces are very
well coordinated. That is why he is ready to face Black's attempts to create
an activity.} f6 ({After} 11... f5 {White's better development allows him to
open up the position by the thematic} 12. h3 Nf6 13. c5 $1 {and arising
complications work well for White. For example, after} exd4 14. cxd6 dxc3 15.
Bc4+ Kh8 16. bxc3 Qa5 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. e5 Bg7 19. Bxa6 Qxa6 20. e6 $16 {
White is dominating.}) 12. Bh4 Bh6 13. Qc2 Bf4 14. Bg3 {and White looks better
here. Black has run out of active, constructive ideas while White has many
useful moves such as Rad1, Bxf4, Qd2, etc.}) ({Black also tried} 10... Qe8 {
but it looks a bit illogical with White's rook being on e1. White has very
pleasant game after} 11. h3 h6 {Black's desire to kick the annoying bishop
back is completely understandable.} ({In a case of} 11... Nf6 {White should
play} 12. Bf1 $1 $146 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4,Gb4b5] This is the optimal set-up in
this pawn structure. White managed to protect his central pawns and is now
ready to start active actions on the queenside by means of Rb1 followed by
b2-b4-b5. If Black spoils the coordination in his camp, White can even
consider opening up the position by playing c4-c5.}) ({Another idea is to
transfer the knight to f7 by playing} 11... f6 12. Bc1 Nh6 13. Bf1 Nf7 {
In the position, White maintains the tension in the center and should just
start his play on the queenside} 14. Rb1 Qe7 ({If Black decides to immediately
strike in the center by playing} 14... f5 {White should just keep his
queenside play going on. The play might continue} 15. b4 f4 16. b5 Nc7 17. bxc6
bxc6 18. c5 dxc5 {all this happened in the game Akl, N (2165) -Borzakian, M 
(2198) France 2004. At this point, White missed the strong} 19. dxe5 $1 $146
Nxe5 20. Na4 $36 {with a solid positional advantage.}) 15. b4 Nc7 {Now I like}
16. Ba3 $5 $146 {maintaining the tension and waiting for the suitable moment
to strike with either b4-b5 or c4-c5.} (16. b5 {would allow} c5 $1 {but not} (
16... Ng5 17. Nxg5 fxg5 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. d5 c5 20. Be3 {White was better in
Gelfand,B (2733)-Movsesian,S (2637) Fuegen 2006}) 17. dxc5 dxc5 {and Black
looks good here Markus,R (2584)-Nakamura,H (2657) playchess.com INT 2005})) 12.
Bc1 Nf6 13. Bf1 {White is better in most of the cases, once they reach this
set-up. Black struggles to create counterplay in this position.} Qe7 ({Another
option would be} 13... Nh5 {when the play might continue} 14. Be3 Qe7 15. Qd2
Kh7 16. c5 $1 {Again, this thematic break works perfectly for White. As I
already pointed out, this idea is very effective when Black's pieces are not
coordinated.} exd4 17. cxd6 Qxd6 18. e5 Qd8 19. Bxd4 $16 {This position was
reached in the game Romanov, E (2554)-Libiszewski, F (2480) Moscow 2008.
White's advantage is out of question. He is better to developed and enjoys a
considerable space advantage. On the other hand, Black's minor pieces are very
passive. This is especially valid for the knights who are out of play.}) 14. c5
$1 {Once again, this thematic break is White's best reaction. Maybe the reader
has already seen that this idea is extremely powerful when Black's knight is
on f6. Our position of interest is reached after} dxc5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. Bxa6
bxa6 {This position has been reached in two games so far. At this point, I
have a simple improvement} 17. Be3 $5 $146 {In this structure, White usually
tries to exchange his e5-pawn for the one on c5. Later on, he enjoys a stable
positional edge due to Black's compromised structure.} Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19.
Bxh6 Rd8 20. Qc1 $14 {with a clear positional pull.}) ({It is important to
know that} 10... Qb6 {could be answered with} 11. h3 Nf6 ({Even worse is} 11...
exd4 {when White can go for the following sequence} 12. Na4 Qa5 13. hxg4 b5 14.
cxb5 cxb5 15. Be7 Re8 16. Bxd6 bxa4 17. e5 {With an obvious advantage.}) 12. c5
$1 {With Black's queen being on b6, this break is even more powerful. A
typical line would be} dxc5 13. Na4 Qa5 14. Bxa6 bxa6 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. Rc1 $16
{White exercises a tremendous positional pressure.}) 11. Bh4 {When Black's
queen is placed on the d8-h4 (instead of being on the e-file) diagonal, it is
desirable to place the bishop on h4.} ({For example} 11. Bc1 {is well met by}
exd4 12. Nxd4 f5 {with a nice counterplay.}) 11... Nh6 {This is by far the
most flexible move. Black has two main ideas: 1) play exd4 followed by f6-f5 2)
play Nf7 followed by h7-h5 and g6-g6, or Bh6 That is why White should play
energetically. Of course, Black has alternatives.} ({The move} 11... Qe7 {
doesn't change the character of the position. Here is a nice example} 12. Bf1
h5 13. h3 Nh6 {Mareco,S (2645)-Zapata,A (2418) chess.com INT 2017 Now,} 14. c5
$1 {was extremely strong. For instance, the sequence} exd4 15. cxd6 Qxd6 16.
Bg3 Qd8 17. Bc4+ Kh7 18. Nxd4 {gives White a large positional advantage.}) (
11... Qe8 12. c5 $1 {By now, the reader must have seen that this idea should
be considered in every single position.} exd4 ({Another possible line would be
} 12... dxc5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 {This position was reached in the
game Gavrilov,A (2484)-Shimanov,A (2520) Moscow 2011} (14... fxe5 {doesnot
change the evaluation. At this point, White should opt for the typical} 15.
Bxa6 $1 bxa6 16. Na4 {making use of Black's spoiled pawn structure on the
queenside.} Rb8 17. Qc2 h6 18. f3 g5 19. Bf2 $16 {White's advantage was
obvious in the game Berczes, D (2501)-Kiewra, K (2421) Budapest 2015}) {
An obvious improvement here would be} 15. Bg3 $1 Qd4 16. Qc2 Be6 17. Bxa6 bxa6
18. Na4 $14 {with a typical pressure for such kind of positions.}) 13. Nxd4
dxc5 14. Nb3 h5 15. Bxa6 bxa6 16. Bg3 {Black was threatening 16...g5 followed
by 17. ..h4.} c4 {this position occurred in the game Bilobrk,F (2372)-Viskic,P
(2222) Sibenik 2008. Now, the simple} 17. Nc5 Ne5 18. Qe2 Qe7 19. N3a4 $16 {
would have allowed White to retains a considerable positional pressure. Sooner
or later the c4-pawn will be lost. White has a lasting advantage due to his
better structure.}) 12. c5 $1 {Again this idea is very powerful here.} exd4 13.
Bxa6 dxc3 14. Bc4+ Kh8 15. cxd6 cxb2 16. Rb1 {After a sequence of pretty
forced moves, White obtained a very promising position due to the very
powerful d6-pawn.} b5 17. Bb3 Bg4 ({Another game went} 17... g5 18. Bg3 f5 19.
Be5 Bxe5 20. Nxe5 Qf6 {Bernal Moro,L (2451)-Bates,R (2387) Hastings 2009.
White could have decided the game with by means of the simple} 21. d7 $1 Bb7
22. exf5 Nxf5 23. Rxb2 $18) 18. Rxb2 a5 19. a4 g5 20. Bg3 f5 21. e5 $1 {
A very strong positional piece sacrifice.} f4 {This position was seen in the
game Guo, Q (2351)-Gu, X (2257) Xinghua 2012. Now, my suggestion is} 22. Rd2 $1
{with s clear edge. White's central passed pawns paralyzes Black's forces.}) ({
An interesting idea would be} 9... h6 {Black intends to bother White's
e3-bishop by playing 10...Ng4. Before doing so, he takes the important
g5-square under control.} 10. h3 {This prophylactic move seems to be the most
flexible approach to the position. White is planning to continue playing
classically. Having more space, he can choose among many useful moves. For
example, his next moves can be Bf1, and Rb1 followed by b2-b4.} (10. dxe5 Ng4
$1 {looks somewhat unclear to me. As the reader already knows, I am not a big
fan of clarifying the position in the center.}) {All three games here went}
10... exd4 {Generally speaking, this exchange is justified when White had
already played the move h2-h3. The reason is simple. If now White plays 11.
Nxd4, Black will follow with 11...Re8 when the natural 12.f3 weakens the dark
squares on the kingside (the situation would have been different with a pawn
on h2). White, however, is not obliged to take with a knight on d4. He can
simply react with} 11. Bxd4 {It turns out that Black has no enough resources
to put pressure on e4. Also, I would like to mention that the misplaced
a6-knight is a very important positional factor. With a knight on d7, instead
of a6, Black would have played 11...Ne5 in this position.} Re8 {Now, White's
best piece arrangement is} 12. Qc2 Nc5 13. Bf1 Ne6 14. Be3 {White has a
pleasant space advantage and manages to establish a very nice coordination on
his camp. Now, he is ready to put pressure on the weak d6-pawn by playing 14.
Rad1. Black must do something urgently.} g5 {Black is looking for an immediate
counterplay. Two games arrived at this position, and Black scored pretty well
here. Nevertheless, the following improvement looks very attractive} 15. Rad1
$1 g4 16. hxg4 Nxg4 17. e5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Ne4 {and Black's position is
very exposed. No doubts White has a fantastic compensation for being a pawn
down.}) ({The move} 9... Qe8 {is covered in Chapter 6.}) 10. Qc2 $5 {I like
this useful move not clarifying the pawn structure in the center.} ({A
top-level game featured} 10. d5 Ng4 11. Bc1 f5 12. exf5 gxf5 13. Ng5 (13. h3
Nf6 14. Bg5 {might be an idea for White.}) 13... Nf6 {with a very complex game
Gelfand,B (2747)-Ding,L (2755) Tsaghkadzor 2015}) 10... h6 {As the reader
already knows, Black wants to follow with 11...Ng4.} 11. dxe5 {I think that
after the inclusion of the moves 9...Re8 10.Qc2 this move becomes an
interesting option. Since White is better developed, he can gain a lot of
space on the queenside - his dream is to play a2-a3 followed by b2-b4 and
c4-c5.} ({Of course, the usual} 11. h3 $5 {followed by 12.Bf1 remains a
completely valid option.}) 11... Ng4 12. Bd2 dxe5 (12... Nxe5 13. Be3 {just
leads to pleasant pull for White. As I have already pointed out, Black can not
put pressure on e4, White the weakness on d6 is annoying.}) 13. a3 {[%cal
Gb2b4,Gc4c5,Ge2c4]} Nc5 14. h3 Nf6 15. Be3 Qe7 16. b4 Ne6 17. Nxe5 Nxe4 18.
Nxe4 Bxe5 19. Rad1 $14 {and White's forces are much better coordinated
Kazhgaleyev, M (2580)-Kavutskiy, K (2388) Cappelle la Grande 2016.} *

