1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Na6 8. Be3 {
[%cal Ge5d4,Gh7h6,Gd8e7] This chapter features some possible sidelines for
Black. I deal with the moves 8...exd4, 8...h6, and Qe7. Despite the fact that
these moves are not so popular, it is very important to examine them. Since
these moves lead to typical pawn structures for the variation, when examining
them, the reader will improve his understanding of the variation.} h6 {We are
familiar with this idea. By preparing the move 9...Ng4, Black wants to provoke
White to clarify the situation in the center.} ({As always, the structure
arising after} 8... exd4 $6 9. Nxd4 {is difficult for Black due to the fact,
that he cannot get the d6-d5 break in a favorable version.Therefore, Black is
doomed to defend a passive position.} Nc5 {Another good example here} (9... Re8
10. f3 c6 11. Qd2 Nc7 ({The move} 11... d5 $2 {fails to work due to the typical
} 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Bb5 $1 Bd7 14. Bxa6 bxa6 15. exd5 $16 {and Black has no
compensation at all Forget,D (1821)-Upper,J (2132) Gatineau 2014}) 12. Rad1 Qe7
{Now, Black is threatening to play 13...d6-d5 since the e3-bishop is hanging.}
({The most convincing way to meet} 12... d5 {which occurred three times in
practice is} 13. Nc2 $1 $16 {just winning a central pawn.}) 13. Bg5 Qf8 ({Again
} 13... d5 {doesn't work because of} 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. exd5 Qc5 16. Bxf6 Bxf6
17. Ne4 $16 {This position was reached in the game Chatalbashev, B (2523)
-Maurer, J (2257) Vienna 2013. White is a healthy pawn up.}) {This position
has been occurred twice. Here I like the following idea which allows White to
put pressure on the weak d6-pawn.} 14. Bf4 $146 {Very interesting move. Before
going to his usual e3-square, the bishop forces Black's knight to the edge of
the board.} Nh5 15. Be3 Nf6 16. Nb3 {with a strong pressure on d6. Black has
no counterplay at all.}) 10. f3 a5 {Black's desire to prevent White from
gaining, even more, space on the queenside is understandable. If Black does
nothing, White has many useful moves at his disposal. For instance, he can
play Qd2, Rfd1, Rfc1, Bf1 followed by b2-b4 and Nc3-d5. The move 10...a5,
however, weakens the b5-square. To make use of this weakness, White should play
} 11. Ndb5 {A typical move for this pawn structure. Black cannot consider
c7-c6 any longer since the d6-pawn would be unprotected.} Ne6 12. Qd2 Bd7 13.
Rad1 Bc6 14. b3 $16 {and Black has very passive position without chances to
generate counterplay Diermair,A (2446)-Sanduleac,V (2386) Skopje 2015}) ({
The move} 8... Qe7 {has been quite popular recently thanks to the efforts of
Greek Grandmaster Banikas. Again, Black puts indirect pressure on the e4-pawn
without placing his queen on the inferior e8-square. It seems to me that
White's best try for an advantage is} 9. Bg5 $5 {It turns out that the
e7-square is not a perfect position for the queen either. Now, Black's best is}
Qe8 ({Other moves are much worse. For example,} 9... exd4 {is well met by} 10.
Nd5 $1 Qd8 11. Nxd4 {Again, the arising pawn structure is favorable for White
since Black can hardly get the d6-d5 break.} Nc5 12. f3 a5 13. Qd2 c6 14. Nxf6+
Bxf6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Rad1 $14 {this position occurred in two games Ragger,M 
(2695)-Bekker Jensen, S (2438) Germany 2016 and classical Gelfand, B (2681)
-Damljanovic, B (2559) Istanbul 2000. White's advantage is beyond any doubt
due to his space advantage and the weak d6-pawn.}) (9... c6 $2 {is just bad
because of the thematic} 10. c5 {which is very powerful here. For instance,
after} exd4 11. cxd6 Qe6 12. Qxd4 {, White is almost winning Pravec, L (2302)
-Rotter, W (2120) ICCF email 2004}) 10. Bxf6 $1 {Surprising idea} Bxf6 11. c5 {
The point behind previous Black move} exd4 {This is the most principled reply.
Of course, Black has several alternatives.} ({The move} 11... dxc5 {was played
in the game Miles, A (2584)-Moreno Carnero, J (2515) Mondariz 2000. White
should have played} 12. Nd5 $146 Bd8 13. dxe5 Bg4 14. Bxa6 $1 bxa6 15. Ne3 Bxf3
16. Qxf3 Qxe5 17. b3 $14 {and despite being a pawn down, White has a better
game. Black's pawn structure is very weakened. Furthermore, the combination Q
+ N works perfectly in such positions.}) ({A symmetrical structure arises after
} 11... Nb4 12. cxd6 cxd6 13. dxe5 dxe5 {This position was reached in the game
Sobirey, M (2013)-Priebe, R (2036) GER email 2005. Usually, in symmetrical
positions, the development and the activity of the pieces are the most
important factor. In this position, White is the one who has a better
development and more active pieces. Now, the simple} 14. Bb5 $146 Nc6 15. Nd5
Qd8 16. Rc1 Nd4 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. f4 $14 {would have promised White a better
game.}) 12. Nd5 Bd8 {This is stronger than} (12... Qd8 13. Bxa6 bxa6 {
Wojtaszek, R (2749)-Banikas, H (2568) Doha 2016 White would be better after}
14. Nxd4 $146 dxc5 15. Nc6 Qd6 16. Qf3 $16) 13. Bxa6 bxa6 ({After the slightly
artificial} 13... c6 {White maintains his initiative. For example:} 14. Qxd4
cxd5 {This move marks the beginning of a forced sequence which leads to a
better ending for White.} ({In a case of} 14... bxa6 15. Nf6+ Bxf6 16. Qxf6
dxc5 {1-0 (39) Yakovich,Y (2540)-Mrdja,M (2450) Cappelle-la-Grande 1996, White
should go for} 17. Rfe1 $146 Be6 18. h4 Qd8 19. Qf4 {when White's attacking
chances on the kingside and Black's compromised pawn structure are more than
sufficient compensation for the missing pawn.}) 15. Qxd5 dxc5 16. Bxb7 Bxb7 17.
Qxb7 Bf6 18. e5 $1 Bxe5 19. Rfe1 Qb8 20. Qxb8 Bxb8 21. Rad1 {and despite the
material equality, this endgame is very annoying for Black Lugovoi,A (2490)
-Manakov,I (2330) St Petersburg 1995}) 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Qxd4 Bg4 16. Rac1 Rb8
17. b3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 {and White was better in Leontiev,A (2360)-Korotylev,A 
(2470) Moscow 1998. His knight dominates over the opponent's bishop.
Furthermore, White has a better pawn structure and controls the only open file
in the position.}) 9. Ne1 $1 {A very strong idea, which seems to promise White
a pleasant pull. It appears that White can easily handle this position without
committing for d4-d5-advance. If Black stays passive, White can follow with
simple moves like Nc2, f2-f3, and Qd2 followed by Rac1 and Rfd1.} Ng4 {Being
in a passive position, Black tries to exchange some minor pieces. Nevertheless,
White is usually happy to part with his passive light-squared bishop.} ({After
} 9... exd4 10. Bxd4 Re8 11. f3 {, we reach again this typical structure. As I
have pointed out on my occasions, the arising pawn structure is usually
favorable for White, unless Black can carry out the d6-d5 break.} h5 12. Nc2 b6
13. Qd2 Nc5 {This position has occurred in the game Rodshtein, M (2528)
-Novikov, S (2564) Dagomys 2008. Now, the natural} 14. Rad1 Bb7 15. Nd5 $14 {
would preserve White's positional advantage.}) 10. Bxg4 Bxg4 11. f3 Bd7 12. Qd2
Kh7 13. Rd1 f5 {Black should play actively. Otherwise, he doomed to a passive
position without any counterplay. Nevertheless, White is better prepared to
open the center due to his space advantage and better development. After} 14.
dxe5 Bxe5 15. Nd3 Bg7 16. Nf4 fxe4 17. Nxe4 $16 {White has a huge advantage.
Later on, he can exchange Black's only active piece by playing Bd4. In such a
case, the dark-squares in Black's camp would be very weak.} *

