1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Na6 8. Be3
Qe8 {[%mdl 32768] Black not only removes the queen from the potentially
dangerous h4-d8 diagonal but also puts pressure on the e4-pawn. Now, we have a
pleasant choice between 9.dxe5 and 9.Re1. As I have already pointed out, I
like options which allow keeping the tension in the center. Nevertheless,
during my work on the current database, I was very interested in going deeper
into the subtleties of the structure arising after 9.dxe5 dxe5. Since this is
a very typical KID structure, I am sure that the reader would be interested in
learning it. Furthermore, I believe that White has managed to achieve a
favorable version of this structure since the black queen is not well placed
on e8. Black should waste time to improve the position of the queen.} 9. dxe5 (
{Of course, I will provide the reader with an extra option - the standard} 9.
Re1 $5 {In most of the cases, this move should transpose to the line 9...Ng4
10. Bg5 which is covered in the next chapter. However, it's important to
examine Black's other choices:} c6 {This move leads to positions which are
similar to the previous chapter.} ({The move} 9... Bg4 {was seen in the game
Van Wely, L (2651)-Muse, M (2460) Kuppenheim 2004. Now, the natural} 10. h3
$146 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nd7 12. d5 f5 13. Rb1 $1 $16 {looks favorable for White
since Black can hardly generate dangerous play on the kingside without a
light-squared bishop. At the same time, White has a free hand on the queenside.
}) ({Usually, the structure arising after} 9... exd4 10. Bxd4 {is favorable
for White. Here is an example:} Qe7 {This position was seen in the game
Guichard, P (2300)-Diamant, A (2486) Malakoff 2010.} ({White's central pawn is
untouchable in view of} 10... Nxe4 $2 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Bf1 f5 13. Qd4+ Kg8 14.
Nxe4 fxe4 15. Rxe4 $16 {with a huge advantage for White.}) {At this point, the
simple} 11. Qd2 c6 12. Rad1 Re8 13. h3 $14 {would have given White a pleasant
advantage.}) 10. h3 $1 {Since Black can no longer play Ng4, White manages to
maintain this favorable structure.} Nh5 (10... exd4 11. Bxd4 {doesnot change
anything in comparison to my comment to Black's previous move. In this
position, a mistake would be} Nc5 $2 {in view of} 12. e5 {when White was
clearly better in the game Milovanovic, R (2451)-McClary, L (2141) Dallas 2001}
) 11. Qd2 Qe7 12. Rad1 Re8 13. a3 b6 14. b4 $16 {White reached an amazing
position in Roiz, M (2605)-Jianu, V (2506) Dresden 2007}) 9... dxe5 {We have
reached on of the most thematic King's Indian structures. Despite the fact
that I have already explained some of the basic ideas for both sides, I would
like to go even deeper. First of all, we should pay attention to the way in
which Black is going to arrange his queenside pawns. He has two main
possibilities: 1) play c7-c6 and try to transfer one of the knights to the
weak d4-square 2) play b7-b6 and try to put pressure on e4 by means of Bb7
followed by Nc5 If Black plays c7-c6, White's main plan consists in gaining as
much space as possible on the queenside. The ideal queenside structure is
being reached after a2-a3 followed by b2-b4 and c4-c5. Later on, White tries
to make use of the open d-file and the weak d6-square. For instance, the
maneuver Nf3-d2-c4-d6 is a thematic idea in the position. Given the fact that
Black's queen is on e8 (instead of e7), in some positions, White can even try
Qd6. On the other hand, as I have already pointed out, Black tries to transfer
one of his knights to d4. There are many possible routes for Black's knights
in this structure. For instance, the maneuvers Na6-c5 (c7) - e6 - d4 and
Nf6-h5-f4 (g7) - e6 - d4 are always an option. With a white pawn on c5, Black
is advised to destroy his opponent's space advantage using b7-b6. Also, it is
important to remember that the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is in
Black's favor. Additionally, I would like to mention that Black often plays
Bg4 followed by Bxf3 to further weaken the d4-square. Now. let's discuss the
structure arising after Black's b7-b6. Obviously, Black intends to put
pressure on the e4-pawn by playing Bb7 and Nc5. As always in such positions,
White will gain space on the queenside and fight for the open d-file. When the
move b7-b6 is played, however, White has the extra option to install a knight
on d5. If Black decides to exchange this knight, White will recapture with the
c-pawn, creating a strong pressure against the c7-pawn. Another option for
Black is to play c7-c5. In this way, he stops White's queenside expansion and
prepares the maneuver Nf6-h5-f4-e6-d4. In this case, however, it turns out
that the control over the d-file and the knight on d5 are much more effective
than Black's time-consuming plan.} ({An alternative would be} 9... Ng4 10. Bc1
Nxe5 ({Playing} 10... dxe5 {with a knight on g4 doesn't makes too much sense.
White has an easy play. For example, after} 11. Rb1 c6 12. b4 Qe7 $6 {we reach
a position which arose in the game Krak, T (2297)-Neuman, P (2471) Slovakia
2012 At this point, White could have played} 13. b5 $146 Nc5 14. Ba3 $36 {
with a clear edge. The pressure along the diagonal a3-f8 is very annoying.})
11. Nd4 Nc5 12. Be3 {As we already know, this structure is favorable for White.
Here is one more example.} Nc6 13. Ndb5 Ne6 14. Nd5 Qd8 15. Qd2 $14 {White was
better in Le, Q (2664) -McShane, L (2664) Wijk aan Zee 2011}) {Here I like
subtle} 10. h3 {White takes under control the important g4-square. In this way,
he prevents Black from playing moves like Ng4 or Bg4.} ({The move} 10. Nd2 {
is another popular direction.}) 10... b6 {This is the most popular move. I
will examine Black's three other common possibilities:} ({The move} 10... c6 {
allows the thematic} 11. c5 $1 {which is very strong here} Nc7 {The knight is
heading for d4.} ({After} 11... Nb8 {, White can go for the thematic} 12. Nd2 {
[%cal Gd2c4,Gc4d6] Here, this maneuver is highly effective since Black's
knights are far away from the d4-square. The play may continue} Qe7 13. Nc4 Ne8
{This position was reached in the game Fier, A (2586)-Cavalcanti, F (2235)
Florianopolis 2017. Now, White should have followed with} 14. Qd2 $146 Be6 15.
b4 $16 {when White is making progress on the queenside while Black's pieces
are completely tied.}) {This position occurred in three games, but White has
never chosen the best} 12. Qd6 $146 {making use of the fact that Black's queen
is not placed on e7. Now, after the following sequence} Nb5 13. Bxb5 cxb5 14.
Bg5 Be6 15. Rfe1 $16 {White's positional advantage is out of question.}) ({
If Black goes for an active kingside play using} 10... Nh5 {White can
immediately play} 11. c5 {Now, the idea to spoil Black's structure by playing
Bxa6 becomes real.} Nf4 {Black insists on transferring his knight to e6.} ({
Hardly a good idea would be} 11... c6 {in view of} 12. Bxa6 $146 bxa6 13. Qa4
$16 {White's advantage is clear. Later on, he can proceed with Rad1 followed
by Rd6.}) 12. Bxa6 bxa6 13. Rc1 Ne6 {This is the critical position on which
depends on the evaluation of Black's entire concept. He hopes that his bishop
pair and the possible knight jump to d4 can compensate the spoiled pawn
structure. White, however, has a powerful idea at his disposal. He should play}
14. c6 $1 Qxc6 15. Nd5 Qb7 {all this occurred in Irwanto, S (2327)-McShane, L 
(2671) Baku 2016 White should have continued} 16. Ng5 $1 $146 {not worrying
about} Qxb2 17. Ne7+ Kh8 18. Qd5 $16 {with much better play.}) ({An
interesting idea is} 10... Nd7 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gc5e6] preparing the maneuver
Na6-c5-e6. Despite the fact that this plan fits into the spirit of the
position, it is rather time-consuming. White can flawlessly continue gaining
space on the queenside.} 11. a3 Nac5 12. b4 Ne6 13. c5 {Gaining more and more
space on the queenside} Qe7 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gd7f8] For the time being Black
delays the move c7-c6 and prepares Rd8 followed by Ndf8. Sooner or later,
however, he must go for c7-c6 because the threat of Nd5 is very annoying.} ({
The immediate} 13... c6 {is well met by the thematic} 14. Qd6 {when after} Nf4
15. Bc4 Bf6 16. Rfe1 a5 17. Rac1 $16 {White's space advantage proved to be
critical in the game Kotanjian, T (2443)-Nalbandian, T (2508) Yerevan 2005})
14. Bc4 c6 15. Ra2 Rd8 16. Rd2 Ndf8 {This position was reached in the game
Milchev, N (2362)-Georgiev, K (2453) Borovetz 2008 Now, the obvious} 17. Rd6 $1
{would solidify White's edge.}) 11. a3 Bb7 ({An alternative is} 11... Nc5 12.
Qc2 Bb7 {In this position, White can opt for the powerful} 13. Ng5 $1 {[%cal
Gb2b4] which has occurred only once. White defends the e4-pawn and prevents
Black from executing the maneuver Nc5-e6-d4.} a5 {This move doesn't prevent
the advance b2-b4.} ({An important line here is} 13... h6 14. b4 $1 Ncd7 ({
The move} 14... Ne6 {is well met by} 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. Nd5 $16 {With a
complete domination.}) 15. Nf3 $14 {It turns out that Black cannot make use of
the d4-square while White's plan is clear - double the rooks along the d-file
and play Nd5.}) 14. b4 axb4 15. axb4 Na6 16. Rab1 h6 17. Nf3 Qe7 18. c5 $16 {
White managed to achieve everything he wants. Dronov, A (2603)-Joppich, U 
(2512) ICCF email 2006}) 12. Qc2 Nh5 (12... Nc5 {transposes to 11...Nc5}) 13.
b4 c5 ({Probably worse is} 13... Nf4 14. c5 $1 Qe6 {Drazic,S (2480)-Efimov,I 
(2426) Trieste 2007 White would be better after} 15. Rfd1 $146 {for instance}
bxc5 16. b5 $1 Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2 Nb8 18. Na4 Nd7 19. Qd3 $16 {After taking the
c5-pawn, White would enjoy a solid edge due to his better pawn structure and
active pieces.}) 14. Nd5 Rc8 {Two games have arrived at this position, and I
like here} 15. Rab1 Nf4 16. Bxf4 exf4 17. Bd3 $14 {with a better game for
White thanks to the powerful d5-knight and the weak f4-pawn.} *

