1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Na6 8. Be3
Ng4 {This is by far Black's most popular option in this system. Given the
possibility, Black immediately starts attacking White's center. White should
play very energetically to maintain the pressure.} 9. Bg5 f6 {Despite the fact
that 9...Qe8 is objectively stronger and much more popular, the positions
arising after 9...h6 are very important and should be studied in detail. In
this case, I suggest} 10. Bc1 $1 {When it works, I always prefer the c1 square
for bishop in this structure. From this square, the bishop participates in the
game without the danger of being trapped. Maybe the reader remembers that in
Chapter 6, with the moves Re1 and c7-c6 included, I suggested the move Bh4. It
turns out, however, that this difference matters. For example, if Black plays
in analogy with Chapter 6 10...exd4 11.Nxd4 f5, White can play the simple 12.
h3. This time, the f2-pawn is protected by the rook, and there are is no
knight sacrifice on f2. Black should play 12...Nh6 13. Bxh6 Bxh6 14.exf5 gxf5
15.Bf3 c6 16.Rb1 followed by b2-b4-b5 with an advantage.} c6 {This structure
was already dealt with in Chapter 5. In this case, however, White's rook is on
f1, instead of e1.} ({After the passive} 10... Nh6 {White prepares his typical
queenside pawn expansion by playing} 11. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} Nf7 {Black was
successful with} ({As I pointed out above, Black cannot create counterplay
using} 11... exd4 12. Nxd4 f5 {in view of the typical} 13. Bxh6 $1 Bxh6 14.
exf5 gxf5 15. b4 $1 $16 {[%cal Ge2f3] followed by Bf3. White has a lasting
pressure on the queenside while Black's kingside counterplay is rather
problematic.}) 12. b4 {White just slowly develops his play on the queenside,
while Black lacks constructive ideas} exd4 13. Nxd4 {It's important to mention
that the tricky} Nxb4 14. Rxb4 c5 15. Rb3 cxd4 16. Qxd4 Re8 17. Qd2 b6 18. Bb2
Bb7 19. f3 $16 {leads to a clear positional advantage for White as happened in
Lautier, J (2663)-Damljanovic, B (2535) Kallithea 2002.}) ({We should always
take into consideration the active} 10... f5 {Unfortunately for Black, this
idea doesn't work tactically.} 11. exf5 gxf5 {other moves are not impressive
as well:} ({The line} 11... Bxf5 12. h3 Nf6 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. g4 Bc8 15. Nxe5
$16 {ended up in extra pawn for White in Martinez,J (1920)-Herzog,K (2077) LSS
email 2008}) ({The move} 11... exd4 {can be answered with the intermediate} 12.
Bg5 $1 {when after} Qe8 13. Nd5 $1 {White develops a dangerous initiative.
Here is an example:} Bxf5 14. Nxd4 Qe5 15. Bxg4 Qxd4 16. Bxf5 gxf5 17. Ne7+ Kh8
18. Qh5 Qxc4 19. Ng6+ Kg8 20. Nxf8 Rxf8 21. Bh6 $18 {Ponting,A (1897)-Herzog,K
(2015) LSS email 2009}) 12. dxe5 dxe5 {this position occurred in Dilleigh,S 
(2126)-Thompson,R (1998) England 2015} ({Apparently, Black's best idea is} 
12... Nxe5 {even in this case, however, after playing} 13. Re1 $14 {White
maintains a solid positional pull due the better pawn structure and slightly
exposes black king.}) {White could have secured an advantage with} 13. Qxd8 $1
Rxd8 14. h3 e4 15. hxg4 exf3 16. Bxf3 fxg4 17. Bd5+ $1 Kh8 18. Bg5 $16 {
White has a huge advantage due to the tremendous activity of his pieces.}) ({
The prophylactic} 10... Kh8 {could be met by} 11. h3 Nh6 12. dxe5 {when Black
must choose between two different structures.} dxe5 {This is the more solid
option. In Chapter 6, we have already discussed a slightly different version
of this structure - Black's knight was on f6, in front of the f7-pawn. Given
enough time, Black would be glad to play Nf7 followed by Na6-c5-e6 and c7-c6.
In this case, the move c7-c6 wouldn't be a positional concession since the
weak d6-square is covered by the f7-knight. On the other hand, Black's plan is
somewhat slow. Also, there is no immediate pressure on White's center. That is
why White can start his queenside play.} ({The structure arising after} 12...
fxe5 {is favorable for White. His plan is clear - attack Black's pawn
structure by making simple moves such as Be3, Qd2, Rfd1, and b2-b4 followed by
c4-c5. Of course, White can also install his knight on d5 whenever he wants.
At the same time, Black has no clear way to develop a kingside counterplay.
Here is an example:} 13. Be3 Nf7 14. Qd2 Nc5 15. Rfd1 Ne6 {This position was
reached in the game Zarsky, K (2050)-Sobek, J (2260) Ostrava 2009 Here, White
should have played} 16. b4 $146 Nf4 17. Nd5 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 c6 19. Nc3 Be6 20.
Rab1 $14 {with a more pleasant game for White, as Black counterplay on the
kingside is very slow.}) 13. Rb1 $146 {This is the best idea in this position.
Here are a few exemplary lines:} Qe7 (13... c6 14. b4 Qe7 15. b5 {White easily
develops his initiative.}) 14. Nd5 Qf7 15. b4 c6 16. Ne3 $14 {with a complex
game, where White maintains better chances. The idea c4-c5 followed by the
maneuver Ne3-c5-d6 is always in the air.}) ({In a case of} 10... Qe8 {White
might obviously play the thematic 11. Re1 that would take us to 10...f6 - line,
however, the position is ready for the thematic} 11. c5 $1 dxc5 ({Another the
important direction here is} 11... exd4 12. Nxd4 dxc5 {otheriwse Black knight
hangs on g4} 13. Nb3 Qe6 14. Nd5 Rf7 {Karr,J (2360)-Grigore,G (2475) Paris 1998
} ({bad is} 14... c6 {in view of} 15. Nf4 Qd7 16. Bxa6 bxa6 17. Qxd7 Bxd7 18.
Nxc5 $16 {With a huge positional advantage for White. 1-0 (35) Barkhagen,J 
(2340)-Winsnes,R (2330) Helsingborg 1991}) {Now, a clear improvement over the
game would be} 15. Bxa6 $1 $146 bxa6 ({the move} 15... Qxa6 {runs into} 16.
Nxc7 Rxc7 17. Qd8+ Bf8 18. Qxc7 $18) 16. f3 {important intermezzo.} ({the
immediate} 16. Nxc7 {loses to} Qe5 $19) 16... Ne5 17. Nxc7 $1 Rxc7 18. Qd8+ Bf8
19. Qxc7 Qb6 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. Rd1 $16 {and Black doesn't have sufficient
compensation for the exchange.}) 12. Bxa6 bxa6 13. d5 f5 14. Re1 $1 {It it
appears that Black kingside play is not dangerous and White was able to obtain
a very nice edge after} f4 15. b3 h6 16. Ba3 $16 {Pogorelov,R (2439) -Larino
Nieto, D (2325) Calvia 2005}) 11. h3 Nh6 12. c5 $1 {A very powerful blow as
you must have seen by now.} exd4 {This is the most principled continuation.
Black hopes to survive in the arising complications.} ({Other moves are not
challenging. For example, after the passive} 12... Nf7 {White starts
destroying his opponent's center by playing} 13. cxd6 b5 {This is not a
suitable moment for taking actions on the queenside since the center is
hanging.} ({Nevertheless, it is already difficult to give Black a good advise.
For example, even after the more reasonable} 13... exd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd6 15. Bxa6
bxa6 16. Qa4 Bb7 17. Nb3 Rad8 18. Be3 $16 {, White retains a clear positional
edge. Auburger,K-Henke,S DESC email 2011}) 14. dxe5 fxe5 15. a4 $1 b4 16. d7 $1
{with huge advantage for White due to his more active pieces and Black's
terrible structure. Arsovic,Z (2430)-Markovic,M (2470) Nis 1995}) ({To a
favorable for White structure leads} 12... dxc5 13. dxe5 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Nc7 15.
exf6 Rxf6 {This position was reached in the game Pheby, I-Kalinsky, S England
1995. Now, the simple} 16. Be3 $16 {would just secure nice edge for White.})
13. Bxa6 dxc5 {This is the most logical continuation. Black sacrifices a piece
for two pawns and a nice center. Other options are worse.} ({In a case of} 
13... dxc3 {White can play} 14. Bc4+ d5 (14... Kh8 15. cxd6 Re8 {occured in
Glicenstein,A-Kozakov,M/Rosny sous Bois 2004/EXT 2005 (36)} (15... cxb2 16.
Bxb2 Nf7 17. Bxf7 Rxf7 18. e5 $16 {M.Gurevich}) {And now, the move} 16. bxc3 {
was necessary. The game might continue} Rxe4 17. Qd3 Bf5 18. Nd4 $16 {The the
activity of White's pieces and his dangerous passed pawn gives him an obvious
initiative.}) ({The attempt to hold the position by playing} 14... Nf7 15. cxd6
Kh8 {doesnot work quite well because of} 16. Bxf7 $1 Rxf7 17. bxc3 $16 {
White is a healthy pawn up. The d6 passed pawn should be decisive. Noori,
A-Moradi,E/IRI 2000/EXT}) 15. exd5 cxd5 16. Qxd5+ Kh8 17. bxc3 {and White is
just a pawn up Gurevich, M-Hansen, C/Groningen 1992}) (13... bxa6 14. Qxd4 ({
Another good idea would be} 14. Nxd4 dxc5 15. Nxc6 $14 {suggested by M.Gurevich
}) 14... Nf7 {Two games have arrived to this position. The most precise here
would have been} 15. Rd1 $1 dxc5 16. Qxc5 Qb6 17. Qc4 $1 {White has a huge
advantage. Besides his bad pawn structure, Black cannot easily develop his
pieces.}) 14. Na4 {I like this move a lot. White is going for a positional
advantage rather than material.} ({The position arising after} 14. Bc4+ Kh8 15.
Na4 Qe7 {is a way more complicated since Black has a strong center while White
experience difficulties to establish a coordination between his pieces.}) 14...
Qe7 {Black follows his concept - instead of immediately regaining the material,
he is playing for a long-term compensation.} ({After} 14... bxa6 15. Bxh6 $1
Bxh6 16. Nxc5 $16 {White is obviously better. He will regain the missing pawn
after which his is just better due to Black's structural defects.}) 15. Qc2
bxa6 16. Bxh6 $5 (16. Nxc5 {good enough for solid edge.}) 16... Bxh6 17. Nxc5
$16 {Again, White enters a structure we are already familiar with. White was
better in Navara, D (2672)-Svidler, P (2746) Baku 2008} *

