1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Na6 8. Be3
Ng4 9. Bg5 Qe8 {This is the principled reaction. Now, White should take care
of his center. Under favorable circumstances, after taking on d4, Black can
play Qe5, putting pressure on White's position.} 10. Re1 $5 {An amazing move,
which I had analyzed back in 2007 while being second of Vladimir Kramnik.
Again, White employs the same idea of not releasing the tension in the center
and trying to benefit from e-file x-ray.} exd4 {Black should immediately
strike in the center if he wants to justify his previous play.} ({Of course,
we should take a look at the alternatives: The continuation} 10... c6 11. h3 {
transposes to Chapter 5.}) ({Again, the move} 10... f6 {should be answered with
} 11. Bc1 Nh6 $6 {This move seems to be too slow.} ({After the usual} 11... c6
12. h3 Nh6 {, we reach a position which has been covered in Chapter 5.}) 12. c5
$1 {Of course! This move always works when our opponent is behind in the
development or has coordinational problems in his camp.} exd4 {This position
arisen in Peralta, F (2546)-Movsziszian, K (2534) Tarragona 2007. At this
point, White missed} 13. Nd5 $1 $146 {when the following sequence is possible:}
c6 14. Bxa6 cxd5 15. exd5 Qd7 16. c6 bxc6 17. dxc6 Qxc6 18. Bf1 $16 {After
regaining the d4-pawn, White positional advantage is beyond any doubts.}) ({
It is important to remember that we should answer the move} 10... h6 {with} 11.
Bh4 ({The drawback of} 11. Bc1 {can be seen in the variation} exd4 12. Nxd4 Qe5
13. Nf3 Qc5 {when White should play 14.Rf1 in order to protect the f2-pawn.})
11... Nf6 {Black returns the knight, pretending that the move 11.Bh4 is a
slight concession. Nevertheless, as it turns out quite often in this variation,
Black wasted a lot of time. That is why White has an energetic solution at his
disposal.} ({In the event of} 11... c6 12. Bg3 $1 {is very strong. The threat
of 13.h3 forces Black to accept an inferior pawn structure.} (12. h3 Nf6 {
less clear.}) 12... Qe7 $6 13. c5 $1 dxc5 14. d5 Rd8 15. Bxa6 bxa6 16. h3 Nf6
17. Nxe5 $18 {and Black was already lost in Ricardi,P (2554)-Matsuura,E (2467)
Vicente Lopez 2001}) 12. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 13. c5 {Of course! Even in this case,
this thematic idea works perfectly for White.} Bg7 {Black prevents White from
playing Nd5 with a tempo.} ({An alternative is} 13... Nb4 14. cxd6 cxd6 {
This position was reached in two game. None of them, however, featured the
natural} 15. dxe5 $146 dxe5 {As I have already mention, in symmetrical pawn
structures, the development and the activity are the most important positional
factor. A possible line would be} 16. Bb5 Qe7 17. a3 Nc6 18. Nd5 Qd6 19. Nxf6+
Qxf6 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. h3 $1 {White has a very pleasant advantage in this
position. He can gradually put pressure on Black's weak pawns. Additionally,
we should mention that Black's bishop lacks perspectives.}) ({Of course, the
move} 13... exd4 {should be answered with} 14. Nd5 {and White obtains a clear
positional superiority after both} Bd8 ({and} 14... Qd8 15. Bxa6 bxa6 16. Rc1
$1 $16) 15. Bxa6 bxa6 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. Qxd4 $16) 14. Bxa6 bxa6 15. Nd5 Qd8 16.
dxe5 dxe5 17. Qa4 Bg4 18. Re3 $16 {White was better in Ovsejevitsch, S (2561)
-Jacek,K (2071) Koszalin 2012}) 11. Nd5 $5 {A creative idea which is connected
with White's previous move} (11. Nxd4 {just leads to a very complex game after}
Qe5 12. Nf3 Qc5 13. Bh4 Be6 {which has occurred in many games.}) 11... c6 {
In my opinion, this is Black's best move since it is difficult to live with
the mighty d5-knight, but other options are very important as well:} ({It
seems that the intermediate} 11... d3 {doesdon't help Black.} 12. Bxd3 c6 ({
After} 12... Bxb2 $2 {Black runs into tactical problems} 13. Rb1 Bg7 14. c5 $1
{Once again, this break works perfectly for White} h6 15. Bxa6 hxg5 16. Nxc7
Qc6 17. Qxd6 Qxd6 18. cxd6 $18 {White got a winning position in Vanheirzeele,
D (2091)-Buchal,S (2273) Caleta 2015}) 13. Ne7+ Kh8 14. Nxc8 Rxc8 15. Bf1 {
If White manages to completely consolidate his position, his long-term
perspectives will be better due to the pair of bishops and the weak d6-pawn.
That is why Black should take immediate actions.} Bxb2 {This is better than} (
15... Nc5 16. Qxd6 Nxe4 17. Qa3 f5 18. h3 Ne5 19. Bf4 $1 Nd7 20. Rad1 {White's
bishop pair and active pieces give him a huge advantage. Kramnik,V (2799)
-Topalov,V (2780) Nice 2008}) {Black is having very good results on practice,
but I have some fresh idea here} 16. e5 $5 $146 {when the following sequence
of moves look logical} dxe5 (16... Nxe5 17. Rb1 $16 {just bad for Black.}) 17.
h3 $1 Bxa1 (17... f6 {should be easier for White} 18. Rb1 Bc3 19. Bd2 Nxf2 20.
Kxf2 Bxd2 21. Nxd2 $16 {In this position the extra piece should be more
important hat three pawns. This evaluation could be explained by the activity
of White's pieces.}) 18. hxg4 f6 19. Bd2 Bb2 20. Qb3 Bd4 21. Nxd4 Qd7 22. Nf3
e4 $1 23. Rxe4 Nc5 24. Qb1 Nxe4 25. Qxe4 $14 {We have an interesting material
imbalance - three pieces for two rooks! Due to the vulnerability of Black's
king, I prefer White here. As a possible idea, he can consider weakening the
long diagonal through g4-g5.}) (11... f6 12. Bf4 {[%mdl 32768] The best square
for White's dark-squared bishop. White has to keep an eye on the d6-pawn.} d3 {
The idea of this move is simple - Black wants to play Ne5 with tempo.} ({
The use of White's 12.Bf4 becomes obvious after} 12... c6 {when White can just
play} 13. Bxd6 cxd5 14. exd5 {So far, White has just one pawn for the piece.
Nevertheless, Black is not developed, and his pieces are completely misplaced.
Here are some examples which illustrate the power of White's initiative.} Qf7 {
0-1 (24) Debashish,D (2472)-Vocaturo, D (2606) Caleta 2017} (14... Qd8 15. c5
Re8 {1/2-1/2 (21) Levin,F (2564)-Vocaturo,D (2417) Bratto 2008} 16. Bc4 Rxe1+
17. Qxe1 $16) (14... f5 15. c5 Qd8 16. Bxa6 bxa6 17. Bxf8 Bxf8 18. d6 $18 {
1-0 (24) Lalic,B (2500)-Bates,R (2378) Hastings 2008}) (14... Rf7 15. c5 Qd8
16. Nxd4 Nh6 17. Ne6 Bxe6 18. dxe6 Re7 19. c6 $18 {1-0 (22) Kasimdzhanov,R 
(2679)-Pruijssers,R (2458) Netherlands 2009}) 15. Bxf8 Bxf8 16. Nxd4 f5 17. a3
Nf6 18. b4 $16) 13. Qxd3 Ne5 14. Qc2 {The position is already stable, and we
can draw some conclusions. White's advantage is obvious. He has a considerable
space advantage and a powerful knight on d5. The opposition between White's
rook and Black's queen along the e-file is also an important factor in this
position. Black's only attempt to create some counterplay is based on the
f6-f5 break. Nevertheless, it is not easy to carry it out in a good version.}
Qf7 {With this move, Black removes the queen from the opposition and
overprotects the important c7-pawn.} ({The immediate} 14... f5 {runs into} 15.
c5 {This move is very logical since Black is not ready to play an open
position.} c6 16. Bxe5 dxe5 17. Ne3 {[%cal Ge3c4,Gc4d6] The structure has
changed, and the knight is heading for the ideal d6-square.} Nc7 18. Nc4 fxe4 {
This position was reached in the game Elsness, F (2491)-Sadler, M (2625) Oslo
2011. At this point, I suggest the logical} 19. Nd6 Qe7 20. Bc4+ Be6 21. Rxe4
$16 {With a serious positional advantage.}) 15. Rad1 c6 (15... Nc5 16. b4 Ne6
17. Bg3 Bd7 18. c5 dxc5 (18... c6 19. Ne3 dxc5 20. bxc5 $16) 19. Bxe5 fxe5 20.
Bc4 $18 {1-0 (55) Savina,A (2389)-Daulyte,D (2306) Tbilisi 2011}) 16. Ne3 Qe7
17. Nd4 Nc5 {Two games arrived to this position, but White has never played
naturally} 18. b4 $1 Ne6 19. Nxe6 Bxe6 20. Bg3 {Kojima,S (2282)-Resika,N (2149)
Budapest 2012 and White should enjoy nice pull thanks to favorable pawn
structure and lack of real counterplay for Black.}) 12. Ne7+ Kh8 13. Nxc8 Rxc8
14. Nxd4 Nf6 15. f3 {We have reached a pawn structure which is known to be
favorable for White. If White manages to consolidate his position by means of
natural moves such as Qd2, Rad1, and Bf1, he will enjoy a stable advantage due
to his bishop pair, space advantage, and the weak d6-pawn. Black's only hope
for counterplay is based on the d6-d5 break.} Qe5 {The most logical move.
Black centralizes his queen with temp and prepares the d6-d5 break.} (15... Nc5
{This move is too slow for the nature of the position. White has the necessary
time to consolidate.} 16. Bf1 ({Another possibility is} 16. b4 Ne6 17. Nxe6
Qxe6 18. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Ga1d1] followed by Rad1. White is better.}) 16... Qe5
17. Be3 Rfe8 18. Qd2 a6 19. Rad1 $16 {1-0 (38) Wojtaszek,R (2640) -Saric,I 
(2573) Novi Sad 2009 CBM 133 [Wojtaszek,R]}) 16. Be3 d5 17. Qb3 {A very
important intermediate move. White connects the rooks, protects the e3 bishop
and puts an annoying pressure on b7. Due to the pair of bishops, he is not
afraid of opening up the position.} ({After} 17. cxd5 $6 Nxd5 $1 18. Bf2 Nf4 {
Black obtains a dangerous counterplay.}) 17... c5 {Black continues playing in
the same fashion. With every single move, he creates new threats. As we know,
however, long-term factors in this line favor White.} ({After} 17... Nd7 {
White can open up the position for his bishops.} 18. cxd5 Nac5 19. Qa3 cxd5 20.
exd5 Qxd5 21. Rad1 Qe5 22. Bf2 $16 {1-0 (48) Csonka,B (2410) -Szajbely, Z 
(2241) Budapest 2015}) 18. Nb5 (18. Nc2 dxe4 19. Qxb7 Qe6 $13 {1/2-1/2 (73)
Arjun, B (2250)-Perpinya Rofes, L (2401) Barbera del Valles 2012}) 18... dxe4
19. Rad1 {With a temporary pawn sacrifice, White overtakes the initiative.} ({
Black manages to create counterplay after} 19. Nxa7 {0-1 (41) Nezad,H (2431)
-Ahmad,A (2271) Khartoum 2016} Ra8 20. Nb5 Nb4 $13) 19... Rcd8 20. Nxa7 Rxd1
21. Rxd1 exf3 22. Bxf3 Ne4 {This active jump is Black's best bet in the
position.} ({The natural} 22... Re8 {is bad because of the following sequence:}
23. Bf2 Ne4 24. Bxe4 Qxe4 25. Re1 Qxe1+ 26. Bxe1 Rxe1+ 27. Kf2 Rb1 28. Kg3 Rxb2
29. Qe3 Bf6 30. Nb5 Kg7 31. h4 $1 h5 32. Nd6 $16 {When Black has no enough
compensation for the sacrificed material. Queen and knight are always
dangerous when they work together. 1-0 (45) Noeth,D (2327)-Barr,E (2128) ICCF
email 2013}) 23. a3 $1 {A very important prophylactic move which practically
kills Black's a6-knight. Now, it turns out that Black fails to obtain a
sufficient counterplay.} (23. Re1 f5 24. Qxb7 Nb4 $132) 23... f5 24. Nb5 (24.
Qxb7 Nd6 25. Qb3 Nxc4 $13 {0-1 (35) Ashwin,J (2431)-Bojkov,D (2542) Groningen
2010}) 24... Nc7 (24... Qxb2 25. Qxb2 Bxb2 26. Bxe4 fxe4 27. Rd7 $40) 25. Nxc7
Qxc7 26. Bxe4 fxe4 27. Qc2 $14 {White managed to parry Black's immediate
threats, and now he has an advantage. The e4-pawn is safely blocked and can be
easily attacked. Also, due to the pawn majority on the queenside, every
endgame would be favorable for White.} *

